FIM (native, required minimum)Sysmon (Windows)Linux (DNS / commands) <p>On the agent (Agents management → Groups → <code>default</code>):</p> <p></p> <pre><code>&lt;agent_config&gt;
  &lt;syscheck&gt;
    &lt;directories realtime="yes" check_all="yes"&gt;C:\Users\user\Downloads&lt;/directories&gt;
    &lt;directories realtime="yes" check_all="yes"&gt;/media/user/software&lt;/directories&gt;
  &lt;/syscheck&gt;
&lt;/agent_config&gt;
</code></pre> <p>Why <code>check_all="yes"</code> is mandatory</p> <p>Without <code>check_all="yes"</code>, Wazuh omits the <code>sha256_after</code> field from the FIM alert. The <code>custom-opencti.py</code> script reads <code>syscheck.sha256_after</code> to query OpenCTI — if the field is absent, no enrichment occurs and the event is silently skipped.</p> <p>Default monitored paths may not have check_all</p> <p>Directories Wazuh monitors out of the box — <code>System32</code>, <code>drivers\etc</code>, <code>Startup</code> on Windows; <code>/etc</code>, <code>/usr/bin</code> on Linux — are configured without <code>check_all="yes"</code>. They generate normal FIM alerts but are not enriched by OpenCTI unless you explicitly redefine them with that attribute.</p> <p>Realtime monitoring — known limitations</p> <p>Do not monitor root paths in realtime</p> <p>Avoid <code>realtime="yes"</code> on <code>C:\</code> (Windows) or <code>/</code> (Linux) — always use specific subdirectories.</p> <ul> <li>Windows: <code>syscheck.max_fd_win_rt</code> (<code>internal_options.conf</code>) caps   realtime handles at 256 (max 1 024). A full-disk path exceeds this   and the agent silently stops reporting changes.</li> <li>Linux: <code>fs.inotify.max_user_watches</code> (typically 8 192–65 536)   limits concurrent directory watches. Monitoring <code>/</code> exhausts it —   look for <code>ERROR: Unable to add inotify watch</code> in <code>ossec.log</code>.   With <code>check_all="yes"</code>, hashing the whole filesystem also causes heavy   CPU/IO load. Check or raise the limit if you monitor many specific paths:   <pre><code>cat /proc/sys/fs/inotify/max_user_watches
sudo sysctl fs.inotify.max_user_watches=524288
</code></pre></li> <li>Linux: <code>/proc</code>, <code>/sys</code>, and <code>/dev</code> are virtual pseudo-filesystems —   do not add them explicitly. Wazuh skips them automatically even if they   fall inside a monitored path (<code>skip_proc</code>, <code>skip_sys</code>, <code>skip_dev</code> are   enabled by default).</li> </ul> <p>Scheduled fallback</p> <p>If you omit <code>realtime="yes"</code>, FIM falls back to scheduled mode (<code>&lt;frequency&gt;</code>, default 12 hours). Changes are only detected on the next scan cycle, not immediately.</p> <p>Recommended paths to monitor</p> <p>The following paths are best-practice additions on top of Wazuh's built-in defaults. Add them to your agent/group config with <code>check_all="yes"</code> to enable OpenCTI enrichment.</p> <p>Windows — Endpoints</p> Path Security reason <code>C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc</code> Hosts file tampering — DNS redirects, C2 persistence <code>C:\Windows\System32</code> System binary replacement, DLL hijacking <code>C:\Windows\SysWOW64</code> Same as above, 32-bit subsystem <code>C:\ProgramData\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup</code> System-wide startup persistence <code>C:\Users\&lt;user&gt;\AppData\Roaming\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup</code> Per-user startup persistence <code>C:\Windows\System32\Tasks</code> Scheduled task persistence <code>C:\Windows\Tasks</code> Legacy scheduled task persistence <code>C:\Windows\System32\WindowsPowerShell\v1.0\profile.ps1</code> PowerShell profile hijacking <code>C:\Users\&lt;user&gt;\Documents\WindowsPowerShell</code> Per-user PowerShell profiles <code>C:\Program Files</code> Application binary tampering <code>C:\Program Files (x86)</code> Same, 32-bit applications <code>C:\Users\&lt;user&gt;\Downloads</code> Primary malware delivery path <code>C:\Users\&lt;user&gt;\Desktop</code> High-exposure user path <code>C:\Users\&lt;user&gt;\Documents</code> Data exfiltration, document-embedded macros <p>Windows — Servers (AD / File Servers)</p> <p>All endpoint paths above, plus:</p> Path Security reason <code>C:\Windows\System32\config</code> SAM, SYSTEM, SECURITY hive tampering <code>C:\Windows\NTDS</code> Active Directory database (AD DS only) <code>C:\Windows\SYSVOL</code> GPO and logon script persistence <code>C:\inetpub\wwwroot</code> Web shell deployment (IIS servers) <p>Linux</p> Path Security reason <code>/etc</code> System-wide configuration — broad persistence vector <code>/etc/passwd</code> User account manipulation, privilege escalation <code>/etc/shadow</code> Credential harvesting <code>/etc/sudoers</code> Privilege escalation via sudo rules <code>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</code> SSH backdoor — PermitRoot, authorized keys path <code>/etc/cron.d</code>, <code>/etc/cron.daily</code>, <code>/etc/crontab</code> Cron-based persistence <code>/usr/bin</code>, <code>/usr/sbin</code> System binary replacement (rootkits) <code>/bin</code>, <code>/sbin</code> Core binary replacement <code>/boot</code> Bootloader / kernel tampering <code>/lib</code>, <code>/usr/lib</code> Shared library hijacking <code>/root</code> Root home — SSH keys, scripts, credential files <code>/home/&lt;user&gt;/.ssh</code> SSH key tampering, <code>authorized_keys</code> backdoors <code>/var/www</code> Web shell deployment (Apache, Nginx) <p>See Syscheck (FIM) for the full attribute reference and noise‑reduction tips (<code>&lt;ignore&gt;</code> rules, <code>report_changes</code>).</p> <ol> <li>Install Sysmon with the project's tuned config:    <pre><code>sysmon64.exe -accepteula -i sysmonconfig.xml
</code></pre></li> <li>Ship the channel to Wazuh:    <pre><code>&lt;localfile&gt;
  &lt;location&gt;Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational&lt;/location&gt;
  &lt;log_format&gt;eventchannel&lt;/log_format&gt;
&lt;/localfile&gt;
</code></pre></li> <li>Ensure the base Sysmon rules are loaded (Step 3).</li> </ol> <p>Detail in Sysmon.</p> <p>Add packetbeat/Suricata for the <code>ids</code> group and/or auditd for <code>audit_command</code>. See Linux sources.</p>

FIMSysmon command lineDNS <p>Get the hash and drop the file in a monitored directory:</p> <pre><code>Get-FileHash .\test.txt -Algorithm SHA256
# copy the hash into OpenCTI, then move test.txt into e.g. Downloads
</code></pre> <p>Wazuh computes the SHA‑256 → the integration queries OpenCTI → an enriched alert appears.</p> <p>Run a benign command that contains a test IP/URL you registered in OpenCTI:</p> <pre><code>ping.exe &lt;your-test-public-ip&gt;
</code></pre> <p>Resolve a test domain you registered:</p> <pre><code>Resolve-DnsName &lt;your-test-domain&gt;
</code></pre>
